				\begin{document}$\sigma_{n,p}$\end{document} are the Seebeck coefficient and electrical conductivity of electrons and holes, respectively [40]. Under the assumption that both charge carrier densities are similar, this means that at the transition temperature, the mobility of holes becomes larger than the one of electrons [65]. At small dimensions also topological surface states can additionally contribute to transport [56, 66, 67]. As the properties of topological transport in bismuth and antimony are still under discussion, further transport measurements will unravel new and exciting effects on the transport behavior of tailored Bi and Sb nanostructures [68]. Figure 8
